<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=12351&amp;p=140793#p140793"><![CDATA[
Well, I felt like checking out what Doom for the SNES does and apparently, the display area not including the status bar is 216x144 pixels large. I did the math and found out that with the 144 y resolution, you could have 39058 bytes for vram updates. A 216x144 screen is 248,832 bytes, so if you divide 248832 by 39058, it takes 6.3708331 frames to update the screen, so the game runs at about 10 frames per second? does clipping the sides of the screen really do anything aside from allowing you to have less tiles to update?<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle">Sik wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><br />I hope you're planning to add a brick to that cartridge because the SNES won't be able to power it =P (unless you want to burn some components)<br /></div><br />It would burn it? I thought that the game just wouldn't have enough power to start or something.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=6683">Espozo</a> — Sat Feb 07, 2015 9:48 pm</p><hr />
