<author><name><![CDATA[tepples]]></name></author>
<updated>2015-02-07T20:50:15-07:00</updated>
<published>2015-02-07T20:50:15-07:00</published>
<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=12351&amp;p=140781#p140781</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=12351&amp;p=140781#p140781"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[Re: Sega Genesis + 32X vs SNES + SD2SNES]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=12351&amp;p=140781#p140781"><![CDATA[
In other words, the &quot;Xbox piped into a TV tuner&quot; solution. Video memory bandwidth would be the limiting factor there.<br /><br />On the other hand, newer games are framed for 16:9. You could have the game render to 256x176 and letterbox the crap out of it. This gives (262-176)*331/2 = over 14000 bytes per frame. At 4bpp, the entire frame is 256*176*4/8=22528 bytes, enough to double buffer a whole 4bpp plane at 30 fps. Dither everything down to <a href="http://www.pixeljoint.com/forum/forum_posts.asp?TID=12795" class="postlink">Dawnbringer's palette</a> and enjoy &quot;state-of-the-art high-resolution graphics&quot;.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=9">tepples</a> — Sat Feb 07, 2015 8:50 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
